I'm sure that practices vary in detail around the world, but UK
practices would have somewhere in the 1/4 to 1/3 of the area of a seam
mined by &quot;pillar &amp; stall&quot; left to prop up the ceiling. Certainly, the
limestones in the Box stone mines (which I've spent a dozen or so hours
wandering around in) are around that proportion. So you'd be looking at
a ~4-fold increase in STRESS. Ah, but you've also got the loss of
confining pressure too; that's going to increase the relative stress in
the column, particularly on the surfaces.

--
